# Visual QA and Acceptance Rule

Before finishing the task, perform visual and functional QA.

## Visual QA

Verify:

- card is centered like the reference;
- card width matches the reference;
- card height matches the reference;
- card border radius matches the reference;
- card background opacity matches the reference;
- card border and shadow match the reference;
- background gradient and glow match the reference;
- brand text matches the reference;
- title size and weight match the reference;
- helper text is readable and correctly spaced;
- inputs match the reference;
- button matches the reference;
- links match the reference;
- icons match the reference;
- registration progress bar matches the reference.

## Interaction QA

Verify:

- button hover works;
- button active state works;
- button disabled state works;
- button loading state works if applicable;
- input hover works;
- input focus works;
- input error state works;
- link hover works;
- checkbox hover and checked states work;
- password visibility button works;
- focus-visible states are clear.

## Functional QA

Verify:

- login still submits correctly;
- registration still works;
- validation still works;
- error messages still show;
- API calls are unchanged;
- routing is unchanged;
- Enter submits the form;
- keyboard navigation works.

## Responsive QA

Test:

- 1920×1080;
- 1440×900;
- 1366×768;
- 1280×720;
- narrow width.

## Completion Report

When finished, report:

1. Changed files.
2. New or updated components.
3. Background implementation approach.
4. Preserved auth logic.
5. Interaction states added.
6. Any assumptions.
7. How to run and verify visually.

## Acceptance Criteria

The task is complete only when:

- login page visually matches the new login reference;
- registration page visually matches the new registration reference;
- dark theme remains;
- UI is real components, not a static screenshot;
- background approach was confirmed with the user;
- interactive states exist where needed;
- keyboard accessibility works;
- forms still work;
- code follows project conventions;
- implementation is responsive;
- no obvious visual inconsistencies remain.
